english:
  title: Reflections on the Road at Yak-yu
  author: Seong Hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Rain falls on the southern and northern villages, turning dust to mud—
    The white dust that flew before now glistens and softens.
    Mulberry trees, verdant and thick, darken the deep lanes,
    Old leaves all picked away, new ones now unfurled.
    Silkworms sleep full on their trays while fair weather spreads,
    The ripened cocoons, thick as earthen jars, fill the rooms.
    At the bed's head the spinning wheel creaks and groans,
    Beyond the gate the barley waves shimmer and sway.
    Riding east to meet the spring wind upon my horse,
    My heart to return to my old garden grows ever more urgent.
    When will the children come out to welcome me home?
    The cherries by the steps must be glowing crimson now.
  footnotes:
    - Yak-yu (악유) likely refers to a place name or locality along a travel route, suggesting the poet is journeying while contemplating memories of home.
    - The poem captures a specific moment in the agricultural calendar—silkworm season coinciding with spring barley ripening—evoking both the rural economy and seasonal change as triggers for homesickness.
